BT||HT|e|va|4|cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|at|^-{ Avoiding Mental Lapses by Agumperz (Andrew Gumperz) }
^-|CP||FP||at|^B@2^Z@3A young reader asks, What causes stupid mental lapses and how can I avoid them? I mean things like counting a suit as 5-4-3-2 around the table, or carelessly opening 1NT (12-14), when holding 16 HCP. How do the experts avoid such lapses? |
PG| ***** 96 ***** |


AT|

We have all been there, or at least I have. On one particularly embarrassing occasion, my partner opened 2D and I passed his presumed weak two bid. Unfortunately, in our methods 2D showed a balanced 19-20 HCP, so we missed an ice-cold game. Deeply humiliated, on the next board I glanced at my hand and quickly opened 1S. After partner had raised me to 4S, I glanced down again to see that my five-card major was actually hearts! Now it is one thing to have a club in with your spades, but it is quite another to confuse spades and hearts! At the time, I missed the strange "coincidence" that my second lapse occurred while I was profoundly distressed from the first one. |
PG| ***** 97 ***** |


AT|

So how do the experts avoid such lapses? They don't. At least they don't do it always. I have seen world famous players revoke, miscount suits, pull the wrong card, attempt to play a hand at NT only to realize after a ruff that they were playing in a suit, etc. However ordinary players certainly do lapse more often. The experts control their lapses because they understand three rules: |
PG| ***** 98 ***** |


AT|

Be alert 
Rehearse basic skills 
Manage your emotion |
PG| ***** 99 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%
HT|e|va|4|cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|at|^-{        Be Alert         }
^-|CP||FP||at|^B@2^Z@3I recently played in the ACBL's national tournament. In the evening sessions the number of blunders went up exponentially across the field. It was not hard to see why--players were so tired they were collapsing on couches during breaks or resting their eyes at the table. Towards the end of an evening session, I came to Andrew Robson's table. Andrew is one of the game's great and highly respected players, but tonight he was exhausted. I could see the deep circles around his eyes, and he was literally having trouble keeping his eyes open.|
PG| ***** 100 ***** |


AT|

But I noticed something else. Andrew would not allow the fatigue to make him careless. He was playing extremely slowly taking extra time over even simple decisions, clearly going over the count again and again until he was sure of his play. Andrew may only have played 80% of his best game but at least it was not 50% which is what would have happened had he given in to the fatigue. I learned a valuable lesson that day.|
PG| ***** 101 ***** |


AT| 

Try to get adequate rest before a game but when you can not, here are some guidelines to avoid blunders: 
1. Pay attention to signs of your own fatigue. A key sign is playing poorly. If you blow a hand you ordinarily make, ask yourself if you are tired. If you are, address the problem immediately. 
2. Drink a cup of coffee, or run around the hotel a couple of times. 
3. Slow down. Double and triple check the count before making a play. 
4. Be kind to yourself. Be satisfied with getting 90% of your best game. Don't expect perfection. 
5. Reinforce your will to succeed. Though your capabilities are compromised, you can still play the best game possible under the circumstances. |
