^-|CP||FP||at|^B@2^Z@3Suppose your opening lead blows a trick. What is worse, your &%$## partner's silly bid caused you to make the unsuccessful lead. While declarer ponders what to do, you silently fume. After several seconds Declarer unexpectedly leads a small card toward dummy. Holding the ace of the suit, you are caught flat-footed. As seconds tick by, your irritation grows as you realize you have given away the location of the ace. In this frustrated state, you are much more likely to blow a second trick than if you had calmly prepared for opener's lead while declarer was thinking. Blunders and emotional distress often go hand-in-hand. Strong emotions interfere with your thinking process, and playing bridge provokes many of them. At various times, I have felt elation, fear, anxiety, worry, anger, humiliation, guilt, and embarrassment while playing. It is impossible to eliminate these feelings, but you can make them come up less often and minimize their effect when they do.|
PG| ***** 109 ***** |


AT|

Before you play, acknowledge that strong emotions impair your decision-making and accept that sometimes you have those feelings. When a strong feeling occurs, acknowledge it and then take time to process it. If you are angry, be angry. Then take a deep breath, picture a virgin tropical beach in your mind (or whatever you do to get over feeling angry). Return to the bridge decision only after returning to a calm mental state. |
PG| ***** 110 ***** |


AT|

Here are some habits to improve your ability to manage emotion. 

1. Remove triggers for strong emotions:
Do not keep a private score. The act of writing down numbers like -1400 and +210 keeps that bad sacrifice and the grand you played in partscore in the fore of your mind. Don't keep score and your mind will let the disasters go more quickly. Save the postmortems for after the session. Rehashing bad results, or worse, trading blame with partner only produces more negative feelings. Give obnoxious opponents the silent treatment. If the silent treatment, does not work, try the "Director!" treatment. Arguing will not improve focus. |
